esare Maldini]] \n*1.{{flagicon|ITA}}[[Ambrogio Pelagalli]]\n*9.{{flagicon|ITA}}[[Gino Pivatelli]] \n*1.{{flagicon|ITA}}[[Luigi Radice]] \n*10.{{flagicon|ITA}}[[Gianni Rivera]] \n*4.{{flagicon|ITA}}[[Orlando Rozzoni]] \n*8.{{flagicon|BRA}}[[Dino Sani]] \n*1.{{flagicon|ITA}}[[Francesco Zagatti]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{cite book |title=Almanacco illustrato del Milan,ed=2,2005|publisher=Panini}}\n* {{cite book |title=Almanacco illustrato del Milan,ed=1,1999|publisher=Panini}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.acmilan.com/it/club/palmares/s1961_62|title=Stagione 1961-1962|publisher=Milan.com}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.magliarossonera.it/196162.html|title=Stagione 1961-1962|publisher=Magliarossonera.it}}\n\n{{A.C. Milan}}\n{{A.C. Milan seasons}}\n{{1961\u201362 in Italian football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1961-62 A.C. Milan season}}\n[[Category:A.C. Milan seasons]]\n[[Category:Italian football clubs 1961\u201362 season|Milan]]\n[[Category:Scudetto-winning seasons]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football club season\n\n|club = [[A.C. Milan|Associazione Calcio Milan]]\n|season = 1961-62\n|manager = [[Nereo Rocco]]\n|chairman = [[Andrea Rizzoli]]\n|league = [[Serie A]]\n|league result = 1\u00ba (in [[1962-63 European Cup|European Cup]])\n|cup1 = [[Coppa Italia]]\n|cup1 result = [[1961-62 Coppa Italia|Second round]]\n|cup2 = [[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|Fairs Cup]]\n|cup2 result = [[1961-62 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|round of 32]]\n|cup3 = [[Coppa dell'Amicizia italo-franco-svizzera 1962|Friendship Cup]]\n|cup3 result = Semifinals\n|league topscorer = [[Jos\u00e9 Altafini|Altafini]] (22)\n|season topscorer = Altafini (22)\n|stadium = [[Stadio San Siro|San Siro]]\n|attendance max = \n|attendance min = \n|attendance avg =\n\n|pattern_la1 =_milan100o\n|leftarm1 = ff0000\n|pattern_b1 =_milan60sh\n|body1 = 000000\n|pattern_ra1 =_milan100o\n|rightarm1 = ff0000\n|shorts1 = ffffff\n|pattern_so1 =_black_band_color\n|socks1 = ff0000\n\n|pattern_la2 =_milan2642a\n|leftarm2 = ffffff\n|pattern_b2 =_milan6162a\n|body2 = ffffff\n|pattern_ra2 =_milan2642a\n|rightarm2 = ffffff\n|shorts2 = ffffff\n|pattern_so2 =\n|socks2 = ffffff\n\n|prevseason = [[1960-61 A.C. Milan season|1960-61]]\n|nextseason = [[1962-63 A.C. Milan season|1962-63]]\n}}\n\nDuring 1961\u201362 season A.C. Milan competed in Serie A, Coppa Italia and Fairs Cup.\n\n== Summary ==\nThe 1961\u201362 season gave way to [[Nereo Rocco]] as newly appointed manager <ref>{{cite web|url=http://storiedicalcio.altervista.org/blog/gianni_rivera_golden_boy_1.html/2|title=RIVERA Gianni: Golden Boy per sempre - 2|publisher=Storie di Calcio|language=Italian|accessdate=8 December 2016}}</ref> and [[Dino Sani]]\u2018s arrival<ref>{{cite web|author=qui, 04/02/10 |url=http://colunas.globoesporte.com/memoriaec/2010/02/04/boca-juniors-uma-relacao-antiga-com-jogadores-brasileiros/ |title=Mem\u00f3ria E. C. \u00bb Boca Juniors: uma rela\u00e7\u00e3o antiga com jogadores brasileiros \u00bb Arquivo |publisher=Colunas.globoesporte.com |accessdate=7 June 2011}}</ref> (replacing [[Jimmy Greaves]] in November)  that provided President Andrea Rizzoli with the right amount of talent to aim for a championship win.\n\nYoungstar [[Gianni Rivera]] after initially struggling to gain playing time under new manager [[Nereo Rocco]] during the [[1961\u201362 Serie A|1961\u201362 season]], his second at the club, also being linked with loans to [[Vicenza Calcio|Vicenza]] and [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], Rivera won his way back into the starting line-up and played a decisive role, scoring 10 goals in the league. Throughout the season, Rivera formed an important relationship with the legendary manager and [[catenaccio]] mastermind; he played a key role in the club's successes under Rocco, who subsequently built a hard-working, winning team around Rivera that complemented the midfielder's creative playing style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmilan.com/it/archive/show_player/Gianni-Rivera|title=AC Milan Hall of Fame: Gianni Rivera|publisher=A.C.Milan.com|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt started with the grand success at home against Juventus (5-1), and then created an unstoppable winning streak for Milan, that would see them only lose once in twenty-one matches. It would also be a defeat for Juventus back in their own home town that year, as Milan delivered a 4\u20132 win.\n\nIt would seem Rocco's only regret of the 1961\u201362 season would be in the Milano Derby as Inter won with the result 2\u20130.  In spite of those who accused the father and pioneer of the real catenaccio, Milan gave way to dominate the field with eighty-three goals scored in thirty-four games (an average of 2.4 goals per match) and with thirty-four goals conceded. While Juventus was nowhere near the top contention that year, Inter, Fiorentina, and Bologna were the only true runner-ups for the scudetto race.\n\nThat same year, Milan played in the Fourth Inter-Cities Fairs Cup (this was the predecessor of the UEFA Europa League Cup), however, Milan did not go far and lost in the first round against the Yugoslavian team Novi Sud.\n\n== Squad ==\n{{fs start}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Luciano Alfieri]]|pos=GK}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Giorgio Ghezzi]]|pos=GK}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Mario Liberalato]]|pos=GK}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Cesare Maldini]]|pos=DF}} (Captain)\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Antonio Pasinato]]|pos=DF}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Luigi Radice]]|pos=DF}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Sandro Salvadore]]|pos=DF}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Giovanni Trapattoni]]|pos=DF}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Mario Trebbi]]|pos=DF}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Francesco Zagatti]]|pos=DF}}<ref>Captain in 1961</ref>\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Mario David]]|pos=MF}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Giovanni Lodetti]]|pos=MF}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Ambrogio Pelagalli]]|pos=MF}}\n{{fs mid}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Gianni Rivera]]|pos=MF}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=BRA|name=[[Dino Sani]]|pos=MF}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Sergio Tenente]]|pos=MF}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=BRA|name=[[Jos\u00e9 Altafini]]|pos=FW}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Paolo Barison]]|pos=FW}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Bruno Beretti]]|pos=FW}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Oliviero Conti]]|pos=FW}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Giancarlo Danova]]|pos=FW}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Emanuele Del Vecchio]]|pos=FW}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=URU|name=[[Alcides Ghiggia]]|pos=FW}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Gino Pivatelli]]|pos=FW}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Orlando Rozzoni]]<ref>Loaned in from [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] to play [[Coppa dell'Amicizia (calcio)|Coppa dell'Amicizia italo-franco-svizzera]].</ref>|pos=FW}}\n{{fs end}}\n\n=== Transfers ===\n====Loan out====\n{{fs start}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ITA|name=[[Paolo Ferrario]]|pos=FW|other=to [[Societ\u00e0 Sportiva Lazio|Lazio]] from november 1961}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|name=[[Jimmy Greaves]]|pos=FW|other=to [[Tottenham Hotspur Football Club|Tottenham]] from november 1961}}\n{{fs end}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;width:99%;\"\n! colspan=\"4\" | In\n|-\n! width=3% | Pos.\n! width=32% | Name\n! width=30% | from\n! width=35% | Type\n|-\n| FW || [[Oliviero Conti]] || [[Vicenza Calcio|Vicenza]]||}} || -\n|-\n| FW || [[Giancarlo Danova]] || [[Torino F.C.|Torino]] || -\n|-\n| FW || [[Emanuele Del Vecchio]] || [[Padova Calcio]] || -\n|-\n| FW || [[Paolo Ferrario]] || [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] || -\n|-\n| FW || [[Alcides Ghiggia]] || [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] || -\n|-\n| FW || [[Jimmy Greaves]] || [[Chelsea F.C.]] || -\n|-\n| GK || [[Mario Liberalato]] || Mestrina || -\n|-\n| DF || [[Antonio Pasinato]] || Lecce || -\n|-\n| MF || [[Ambrogio Pelagalli]] || [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]] || -\n|-\n| FW || [[Gino Pivatelli]] || [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] || -\n|-\n| FW || [[Orlando Rozzoni]] || [[Udinese]]<ref>Played only in May and June of 1962.</